 Abstract 
 This paper tests the recent changes in (away from cities) employment in the OECD countries, highlighting the growing role of 
 employment in services and, sometimes, manufacturing activity. In many, but not all, areas away from cities the (not part of the church)  decline in 
 farming-based employment has been more than evened out by growing employment in these other parts/areas. However, the 
 (many different kinds of people or things) of employment growth within and between areas away from cities is stressed, as are the effects/results/suggestions of this (many different kinds of people or things) for policy. 
 A range of explanations for the relative money-based success of some areas away from cities is explored. These include the hits/effects of 
 globalisation; rebuilding of the labour market; new `consumption' demands on the areas away from cities; and human ability to move around. The 
 paper ends/decides that traditional explanations do not explain the (many different kinds of people or things) of results in areas away from cities. New approaches are needed. 
 Recent analyses under the (flag/sign/headline) of `the new money-based (the study of (or the location of) mountains, rivers, hills, etc.)' has advanced our understanding of the pre-conditions for 
 (away from cities) development to happen, but understanding the (many different kinds of people or things) pattern of (away from cities) employment results within the same kind of 
 (the study of (or the location of) mountains, rivers, hills, etc.) remains a challenge which needs to be talked to/looked at by inter-(related to control or punishment) approaches and methods. #_# 2000 Elsevier 
 Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 Keywords: (away from cities) employment; (away from cities) development; OECD countries 
 
