 1.1. The changing big picture  for (away from cities) development 
 The attention given to (away from cities) development in OECD 
 countries has steadily increased over the past ten years, a 
 period of (large/relatively large) change at both worldwide  and 
 (related to Europe) levels. Liberalisation and globalisation are 
 driving worldwide  trade and capital movements and the 
 worldwide  division of labour and signiÂ®cant market changes/recalculations follow from this. Partly linked with these (popular things/general ways things are going), 
 major changes in sets of rules affecting (away from cities) 
 areas are happening. These market and policy changes 
 mean major challenges, as well as some new opportunities, for (away from cities) (groups of people/animals/things). The ability (to hold or do something) of (away from cities) 
 people to respond to possible opportunities and 
 threats by creating new sources of income and 
 employment to replace (lowering in number/getting worse) employment in farming, other first (or most important) businesses, some services (e.g. 
 banking, (related to sending and receiving phone calls, texts, etc.), wholesaling) and manufacturing is a critical issue both for (away from cities) people and 
 for policy makers and (away from cities) development (services businesses/government units). 
 The (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of the recent past in OECD countries 
 is that some areas away from cities are 'better placed' than others 
 to change to fit these processes of `opening up' and the 
 resulting exposure to external forces, although 
 the (proof that one thing definitely causes another) factors are not obvious. Among the 
 explanations of (away from cities) success we can Â®nd those focusing on factor gifts, factor prices, creative abilities (to hold or do something), good luck, `social' capital, nice things, 
 closeness to rich city-based  (groups of people/animals/things) with increasing (way of living) demands on areas away from cities, etc. 
 Areas away from cities differ very (much) in their money-based 
 structure and activity, their natural and human 
 useful things/valuable supplies, the (off to the side)ity of their location (and 
 hence market (possible greatness or power) and transport costs), their 
 (related to information about people) and social facts or conditions (that surround someone), in other 
 words, their general 'initial conditions'. Therefore, 
 they are affected in different ways, and to different 
 extents, by the external forces with which they interact. Policies and support structures for areas away from cities must 
 more and more recognise this (many different kinds of people or things) of conditions and 
 results. It follows that knowledge and understanding of the processes involved, and local responses to 
 them, becomes a important element in the improvement 
 of policy and local action. 
 
 More and more, areas away from cities are expected to develop 
 their own analyses of their strengths, weaknesses, 
 opportunities and threats, and change their own plans and action plans to deal with them. This is a 
 general habit/desire, caused by the lack of described/explained 
 knowledge and solutions at the `centre' as well as 
 by Â®scal restrictions. A critical question for local 
 actors is the dual one: how can they best (make small) 
 bad effects of globalisation and how can they best 
 take advantage of new opportunities? A related question is what room for manoeuvre do they have in an time 
 where the big levers often seem to be beyond their 
 control? 
 2. Trends in (away from cities) employment 
 2.1. Introduction 
 In order to identify and analyse (popular things/general ways things are going) in (away from cities) 
 development, the OECD established a land-based 
 big plan/layout/dishonest plan in which 2000 areas, covering the whole 
 (land area owned or controlled by someone) of the OECD countries, are identiÂ®ed. These 
 areas are grouped into three types according to their 
 share of population living in (away from cities) communities: 
  Mostly (away from cities) areas: over 50% 
  Significantly (away from cities)or `intermediate'regions: 15Â±50% 
  Mostly urbanised areas: below 15% 
 By grouping areas in this way, each type of area 
 contains some (away from cities) and some city-based  communities, 
 although to different degrees (Meyer, 1997). It is this 
 OECD classiÂ®cation which is used throughout this 
 paper. 
 2.2. General (moves in a particular way/becomes popular) 
 The (lowering in number/getting worse) relative importance of farming in 
 areas away from cities is continuing mostly due to adoption of 
 new technology and the growth of other parts/areas. The 
 OECD work on land-based indicators of (away from cities) employment showed that in only three OECD countries did 
 farm-related account for over 25% of the labour force in 
 mostly (away from cities) areas in 1990. Very differently, 
 industry accounted for more than 25% of employment 
 in such areas in seventeen countries, while services 
 accounted for more than 25% of employment in all of 
 them, and over 50% in 18 (OECD, 1996, p. 46). 
 
