 The same OECD studies also showed that between 
 1980 and 1990 the rates of growth of employment in 
 mostly (away from cities) areas went beyond those in mostly urbanised areas in three of the 15 countries for which data was available (Huillet, 1997, p. 
 342). More recent work which disaggregates these 
 (away from cities) areas shows clearly that even among the most 
 `rural' types of (away from cities) area, some have experienced 
 growing employment while others have experienced 
 declining employment (and sometimes population). 
 For example, Cunningham and Bollman (1997) show 
 that `there is a wide difference/different version in employment growth 
 among the different areas of Canada, independent of 
 their degree of (away from cities)ity', with rates of employment 
 growth in mostly (away from cities) areas ranging from 
 Ã20 to 70% (p. 57). Schindegger and Krajasits (1997) 
 show a almost the same  pattern of growth in Austria, where 
 rates of employment growth range from Ã19 to 14% 
 in the (away from cities) areas (p. 174). Table 1 summarises the 
 data for Canada, which is not unexpected. 
 Although this (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) is both surprising and 
 encouraging, two warnings are needed/demanded. First, it 
 remains true in most countries that employment has 
 grown faster in mostly city-based  areas than in 
 mostly (away from cities) areas, and that, in general, it is 
 the signiÂ®cantly (away from cities) areas which have experienced 
 the most fast employment growth. In the (away from cities) 
 areas only the city-based  communities are growing Ã 
 (away from cities) communities are losing both population and 
 employment. According to Irmen (1997) 
 ``rural communities within mostly (away from cities) 
 areas are the losers in (related to space or existing in space) development F F F 
 
 These (away from cities) communities lose population and 
 employment, whereas the (away from cities) communities in 
 other types of areas (mostly city-based  and 
 intermediate) gain in national importance'' (p. 28). 
 In urbanised areas, `rural' communities are growing 
 because they are located in an urbanising (surrounding conditions) 
 and benefit from it. Second, there has also been a 
 continuing employment shortage in many areas away from the cities of 
 the richer countries Ã reflected in a net commuting 
 balance with city-based  areas. Areas away from the cities often continue to 
 be net suppliers of labour to city-based  areas (Schindegger 
 and Krajasits, 1997, p. 168). 
 Other labour market changes worth brieÂ¯y commenting on include: a fall in once-a-year hours worked per 
 person; an increase in self-employment and part-time 
 work especially among women; a rise in long-term 
 and youth unemployment; and the feminisation of the 
 labour force Ã women are playing an ever larger role 
 in the labour force. Although general (popular things/general ways things are going), they are 
 also obvious in areas away from cities. 
 The main points to note at this stage are: 
 1. We cannot generalise about the development or 
 growth experience of (away from cities) areas. We cannot 
 assume that they will unavoidably experience 
 declining employment and population Ã the 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) is that some will succeed and others will 
 even grow faster than the fastest growing city-based 
 area. (places that are off to the side) are not doomed to be constantly falling behind areas in money-based terms, nor are 
 centres (already decided beforehand to happen) to be constantly in the lead. 
 2. Differential results within broad areas are not 
 
