 generally (named after/discovered by/caused by) policy differences Ã in 
 many cases the same policy government produces very 
 different results in different places Ã real 
 processes of money-based, technical and social 
 change are involved which are often independent 
 of policy or even in spite of policy (for example, in 
 the EU the growth of farm household pluriactivity 
 in the 1980s was not encouraged by policy). That 
 is not to say that policy changes and putting into use are insigniÂ®cant factors, especially when they 
 are clearly combined with market and community forces and are Â¯exible enough to deal with 
 varied (away from cities) conditions. 
 3. Some areas away from cities (show or prove) (large/relatively large) ability to change to fit quickly changing external conditions, (even though there is the existence of) well-known handicaps. 
 4. At least in terms of direct employment, (away from cities) 
 people now work in the manufacturing and the 
 (businesses)s in almost all of the EU. However, 
 some areas may `depend' on farming (the 
 major export base) even though few are directly 
 employed in it. 
 In Europe, rebuilding is happening in farming, 
 agri-food and food retailing and distribution parts/areas. 
 There is also a general move/change to a service-based (process of people making, selling, and buying things) in which the information and knowledge based 
 businesses play an increasing role. Linked with this is a 
 de-materialisation of production (i.e. any good one 
 buys has a higher `services' part than in earlier 
 20 years), a de-linking of money-based growth from consumption of raw materials, a dissociation of Â®nancial 
 world/area/ball from the `real (process of people making, selling, and buying things)', and an internationalisation of savings-investment Â¯ows and of relations in 
 commercial and knowledge worlds/areas/balls. Although many 
 of these are not new features of (away from cities) (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) (for 
 example, areas away from cities have always been open to savings/investment Â¯ows to cities), new elements concern 
 the globalisation of these Â¯ows, the reduced power of 
 areas and nation states to inÂ¯uence them and the 
 strengthening internationalisation of relations in commercial and knowledge worlds/areas/balls which both threatens 
 many local commercial and knowledge based activities and provides them with new (non-local) opportunities. 
 De-appeared production (in the sense that personal demand is moving/changing from products (that are bought and sold)  consumption to 
 services consumption) in the form of tourism and 
 
 recreational businesses have been especially important in the richer countries and much of this is based on 
 new `consumption' uses of the countryside. However, 
 this is not to argue that production activities do not 
 remain important both in terms of their money-based 
 signiÂ®cance and in terms of perceptions of (away from cities) 
 people. 
 2.3. There is a steady and long term decline in 
 farming-based employment 
 The long term and generalised decline in farming-based employment is well recorded/supported. In the 1980s 
 once-a-year rates of decline were between 3 and 4% in 
 Japan, Finland, and Austria. In the EU, farming-based 
 employment has (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) by around 2Â±3% per year 
 over the past ten years (Post and Terluin, 1997, p. 310). 
 In 1990, farming-based employment was less than 
 10% of total employment in all EU countries except 
 Greece (23%), Portugal (20%), Ireland (15%) and 
 Spain (11%) (op. cit., p. 308). What's more, in all 
 countries the extent of farming-based employment is 
 (made to appear much bigger, worse, etc., than it really is) because the Â®gures include pluriactive 
 farmers and farm families for whom farming may 
 provide but a small part of/amount of household income. 
 In the EU-12, a sample of 7000 farm families 
 pointed to/showed that just under half of all farm families 
 earned more than half of their household income 
 from farming in 1987 (Bryden et al., 1994). 
 Anyway, it is clear from differential working well 
 data that there is still (large/relatively large) room for further 
 labour savings in farming even without major 
 changes to the CAP. More than that, in the 10 Central 
 and Eastern (related to Europe) Countries (CEECs) which 
 have applied to join the EU, a quarter of the labour 
 force is still working at farming (9.5 million people) creating only 8% of GDP: if the CEECs 
 approach the average working well of the present 
 EU-15, then about 3 million people would leave 
 farming over a period of years. It is not beyond 
 the bounds of possibility, based on past experience, 
 that in East, West and Central Europe as a whole more 
 than 6 million people could leave farming in the 
 next ten years. 
 The purpose of stating this is to raise the question, if 
 not in farming, where are the jobs in areas away from cities going 
 to come from; and how might policy best help in the 
 process of change? 
 
