 2.4. Employment in (away from cities) tourism has been 
 increasing 
 In a few OECD countries, employment in tourism 
 goes beyond that in farming in all types of area. This 
 is the case in the mostly (away from cities) areas of 
 Austria, US, Germany and Switzerland (see Table 
 2). More than that, tourism employment has been growing 
 in all types of (away from cities) area (with the exception of 
 Finland) throughout the 1980s; once-a-year growth rates of 
 3% or higher were recorded in Germany, Spain and 
 Switzerland (Bontron and Lasnier, 1997, p. 436). 
 2.5. Mixed experience with other services 
 In all OECD countries employment in services has 
 been growing. This (popular thing/general way things are going) is reÂ¯ected in the mostly (away from cities) areas where most employment growth 
 during the 1980s was due to net increases in the 
 (businesses) (Meyer, 1997). In all (away from cities) areas the 
 growth of most services similar things that at national 
 levels. The main exception is business services 
 (including knowledge and information based services); this tends to be the high value-added, highwage element of the (businesses), and is heavily 
 under-represented in areas away from cities (Cunningham and 
 Bollman, 1997). Some people expect such services 
 to rule all employment after 2000; for example, 
 projections in Finland in 1995 suggested that by the 
 year 2000, 93% of all work would be `information 
 
 189 
 
 work' (Bryden, 1997 p. 448). However, questions 
 remain about the linkages between this type of work 
 with other parts/areas, and about its exact deÂ®nition. 
 Public services, including education, health and 
 public management, are important employers in 
 many areas away from cities. These parts/areas grew quickly during 
 the 1980s, but that growth appears to have been 
 stopped or even reversed in many areas in the 
 1990s. Employment (moves in a particular way/becomes popular) in other person services, especially retailing and personal services, tend 
 to be linked to population levels and changes. 
 A critical question is whether areas away from cities can participate in the growth in employment in services. In 
 principal this should be helped by the quickly 
 increasing access to, and signiÂ®cant cost reductions 
 in, digital (related to sending and receiving phone calls, texts, etc.), linked in turn to the 
 `Information Highway'. However, (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) on the 
 adoption of these technologies by (away from cities) actors, and 
 especially of the content and hits/affects of their use, is 
 rather rare/not enough. Bryden (1997) identiÂ®es some 
 cases where investment in Information and Communications Technology (ICT) has created employment 
 opportunities in areas away from cities. The focus is placed 
 upon opportunities rather than job creation (by itself/in and of itself)  as it 
 is the hit/effect of ICT on the (wanting to beat others in contests) of (away from cities) 
 businesses/projects in general and the hits/effects on employment 
 of ICT adoption and use which is important for the 
 future of areas away from cities. A main point seems to be that 
 signiÂ®cant employment losses as well as gains can be 
 linked to ICT and, at least sometimes, gains may 
 go beyond losses. Public policies at both national and 
 local levels can make a difference to the direction of 
 these net effects. For example, the helping action of the 
 Highlands and Islands Development Board (HIDB) 
 and later the Highlands and Islands Business/project (which 
 succeeded HIDB) in investments in digitalising the 
 telecom network, and targeting new types of business/project which could use the network, appears to have 
 had good effects (see Sproull et al., 1996). This 
 supports (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of proÂ®table relocation of (related to sending and receiving phone calls, texts, etc.)-intensive businesses/projects in (away from cities) America 
 (Salant and Marx, 1995). 
 3. Explanations of (away from cities) employment changes 
 The changes in (away from cities) employment in OECD countries are of more than passing interest. They are the 
 
 190 
 
 J. Bryden, R. Bollman / Farming-based Money flow 22 (2000) 185Â±197 
 
 opposite of what was expected, if not in terms of 
 farming-based employment, then certainly in terms of 
 growth in manufacturing and services employment in 
 many areas. More than that, there has been a surprising 
 (quality of changing over time or at different places) in results. They are not agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with 
 the (statements about the future) of core-edge/edges models or, in fact, 
 new-classical models, of development patterns. The 
 `New Money-based (the study of (or the location of) mountains, rivers, hills, etc.)' models have created 
 pictures/situations where (away from cities) development will happen 
 (Krugman, 1993, 1999; Kilkenny, 1993, 1998, 
 1999) but the problematique remains Ã how to 
 explain differential money-based performance among 
 (away from cities) places with almost the same  features of (the study of (or the location of) mountains, rivers, hills, etc.), 
 settlement and (off to the side)ity with respect to metropoles. Although Kilkenny's recent work in particular 
 opens up important new questions, new information, 
 and explanation, is needed to explain the loss of competitive 
 advantage in some areas away from cities, and its collection in 
 others. 
 Some of the key explanatory chapters in the book 
 deal with issues such as education levels, (small groups of possible customers), networks and (way of living) choices as a means of 
 exploring the differential performance of (away from cities) 
 areas. In many cases, the Â®ndings are almost the same  and 
 point to the need to view (away from cities) employment changes 
 both within a set of worldwide  and national changes, 
 commonly termed `restructuring', which have speciÂ®c 
 (away from cities) hits/effects and with reference to micro-(related to a large area) 
 (features/ qualities/ traits). For example, in their work McGranahan and Kassel (1997) decide that, (even though there is the existence of) the long 
 standing focus put upon group of workers education as a 
 key to money-based (moving ahead or up), high (related to a large area) education levels offer a limited advantage. Money-based development may be just as dependent upon local 
 facts or conditions (that surround someone) such as closeness to industrial districts 
 or expanding city-based  centres, good/willing climate and 
 nice things as local education levels. Through examining (way of living) choices and (away from cities) job creation, Persson 
 et al. (1997) identify three factors which lead to 
 increasing (using different things): internationalization and 
 organization of money-based activity; (many different kinds of people or things) of (ways of living) and ability to move around patterns among people; and policy 
 (creation and construction/ group of objects) and practices (p. 146). 
 Basically there are three main groups of explanations of (away from cities) employment change. The Â®rst group 
 relates to the hits/effects of globalisation and rebuilding, and the second to new `consumption' functions of 
 the countryside in the richer countries. These two 
 
 groups both relate to external demand forces. The 
 third group of factors is the local `swift-footedness' 
 (either public or private business-starting) in some 
 communities that is not well understood or measured. 
 Clemenson and Lane (1997) identify (the creation of/the beginning of the existence of) (small groups of possible customers) as a means of using (for selfish reasons) 
 potential beneÂ®ts of each of these groups. Special place/good job 
 markets can both respond to the external demand 
 forces, encouraging a re-examination of the opportunities offered by any one place and use local 
 business-starting to create a successful marketing 
 plan. 
 3.1. Hits/effects of globalisation 
 Although the internationalisation of money-based 
 activity has been happening for centuries, globalisation1 is a recent thing/event which has intensiÂ®ed 
 during the 1980s and '90s. Whereas internationalisation refers mainly to trade in products (that are bought and sold)  and services the 
 production of which was organised within national 
 (processes of people making, selling, and buying things), globalisation involves `functional (combination of different things together that work as one unit) between (in other countries) broke up money-based 
 activities' (Dicken, 1992). Although much attention 
 has been paid to the globalisation of manufacturing 
 activities, it is obvious that globalisation has also 
 happened in important business services such as 
 banking, insurance, advertising and communications. 
 Globalisation is marked in part by the reduction 
 of the cost of space due to the reduction in the cost 
 of transportation and communication. Before the 
 beginning of globalisation, high transportation and communication costs protected some (away from cities) workers from 
 competition, and (in almost the same way) were protected from competing in city-based markets by the same high costs. 
 New technology has caused signiÂ®cant reductions in 
 the costs of transportation and communication. 
 Although (related to computers and science) change is not new, it is the 
 focus on transportation and communications that 
 makes globalisation hit/effect signiÂ®cantly on (away from cities) 
 areas. 
 While internationalisation was greatly boosted in 
 the late 19th century by the development of transport 
 technology (steam ships, railways, refrigeration), globalisation has been helped by the reduction in 
