 average taxes/import taxes and other trade (blocking things) after the Second 
 World War2, by the development of ICT, and linked 
 with the growth in trans-national corporations (TNCs). 
 These changes mean that capital can, in way of thinking/basic truth/rule at 
 least, be got together wherever the costs of production 
 are the lowest and where social and (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) 
 restrictions are least. The parts of a product (or service) can more and more be manufactured in 
 different international locations and got together at one 
 spot, either through the growth in TNCs or by (paying someone else to do something) and `just-in-time' ways of doing things of the new 
 production system and forms of `Â¯exible (focusing on doing one thing very well)' (Piore and Sabel, 1984). Although such money-based links are established and maintained in many 
 and different ways, the very important features of worldwide 
 money-based rebuilding are carefully thought about/believed to be its 
 `post-Fordist' nature, Â¯exibilisation, and the international scale of the production and manufacturing 
 processes (Gertler, 1988; Bernat, 1993; Cappellin, 
 1994). 
 A second and a little bit related feature of 
 money-based life today is the speed of change and 
 connected disturbance and doubt, although western Europe has gone for more than 50 years without a 
 major war. Sources of disturbance and doubt 
 include the separation of the `real (process of people making, selling, and buying things)' from 
 the `symbol (process of people making, selling, and buying things)' of international Â®nancial 
 Â¯ows and transactions3; the big changes in the 
 USSR and Eastern Europe which have changed the 
 nature of (related to Europe) space; (not having a steady, trustworthy government) in 
 the Middle East and Africa; changes in the worldwide 
 (surrounding conditions) linked to air-related pollution and the 
 `greenhouse effect'; and continuing trade arguments 
 (Dicken, 1992). 
 
 2 
 In 1940, the average tax/import tax (taxes charged and collected on imports) on products (that are bought and sold) 
 was about 40%; after the GATT Uruguay round of trade talks 
 (1986Â±92) it was about 5%. There has at the same time been a 
 growth in non-tax/import tax (blocking things) to trade such as quotas, import 
 licences, and different legal/law-based devices. 
 3 
