 3.2. Why does globalisation matter for areas away from cities 
 and people? 
 Why does this matter for areas away from cities? First and 
 best because it has effects/results/suggestions for employment 
 and business/project. Because capital is more and more mobile 
 (in other countries), while labour remains (compared to other things) not moving and tied to place, at least two habits/desires can be 
 watched/followed. First of all, there is downward pressure on 
 real wage rates, especially in low-skill pieces/parts of the 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things) which tend to be over-represented in (away from cities) 
 areas. Secondly, there is a relative shortage of investment capital in high cost producing countries and 
 areas which are unable to maintain their competitive 
 edge (in other countries). So, some areas away from cities are more and more being seen as sources of labour; labour that is low 
 cost, reliable and unorganised (Glasmeier, 1993), while 
 some industrial labour markets such as those mainly located in early industrialised areas are being by-passed 
 by the current processes of production (Urry, 1984). 
 The processes of globalisation and rebuilding 
 have impacted on almost all areas of money-based life, 
 public and private, and are usually recognised in the 
 downsizing, re-structuring and (reasons) of businesses, institutions and organisations over the last few years 
 Ã and changing labour market conditions have followed from this. 
 3.3. Rebuilding of the labour market 
 The rebuilding of the labour market has had 
 common effects in most industrial nations, although 
 the hit/effect on areas away from cities has been (made different) by 
 greater dependence on Â®shing, forestry, mining or 
 farming and the degree to which capital had already 
 penetrated the local (process of people making, selling, and buying things). Common elements 
 include the rise of unemployment and the changing 
 nature of work (Pahl, 1984). An increasing number of 
 jobs are contract-based, (for only a short time), and casual, such 
 that an increasing proportion of the group of workers has two 
 or more income-earning activities that are part-time 
 and provide limited social beneÂ®ts. As heavy industry 
 declines and information-based activities expand, the 
 nature of work is changing, with a clear/separate rise in 
 employment opportunities in the (businesses), even 
 in areas away from cities, and a decline in manual labour. (even though there is the existence of) 
 this, manufacturing is still important in terms of local 
 employment. Much deskilling has happened and 
 
 192 
 
 J. Bryden, R. Bollman / Farming-based Money flow 22 (2000) 185Â±197 
 
 where reskilling has happened it has been selective and 
 particular to favoured locations (Newby, 1987). In this 
 huge move/change in labour market structures the participation of women has generally increased which, 
 together with the growth of (belief in women's power), has added/has given 
 to an important move/change in (male/female status) relations and household 
 maintenance (Barthez, 1982; Whatmore, 1990). For 
 most parts of labour market change, there is an 
 equal effect in areas away from cities. 
 3.4. The changing role of the state 
 Globalisation is also changing the role of the nation 
 State. National borders are less (connected/related) in a world of 
 international Â®nance and worldwide  liberalisation of trade, 
 the laws of which are serious and stubborn together at the 
 international level rather than by single countries. 
 Governments are more and more called upon to secure/make sure of 
 participation in world affairs by upgrading communications and transportation (set of machines)s, agreeing 
 to international (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) gives/agrees and programs, 
 and (causing agreement with) legal and technical difÂ®culties between trading partners. The pressure to remain `competitive' in the (world-wide process of people making, selling, and buying things) has led to pressure to 
 reduce taxes and other heavy loads on the (related to big business) part/area, 
 and new demands for increased workers investment. Governments appear to be shifting some of their 
 responsibilities while shedding others, in an effort to 
 balance the budget in a time of Â®scal problem (OECD, 
 1993). The (old/allowing to get old/getting older) of people/of the group and high levels of 
 unemployment have added to pressures on public 
 budgets in many OECD countries. Common responses 
 involve the rebuilding of defence, social welfare, 
 health and education, as well as efforts to move away 
 from granting permanent payments to (lowering in number/getting worse) parts/areas (farming, heavy industry) towards an `investment approach' through which people, parts/areas and 
 areas can be helped to improve their competitive 
 position. The role of governments is more and more to 
 help development rather than to direct it, to 
 cooperate with other nations for trade purposes, 
 and to start partnerships with local groups, including local government and private business, to stimulate money-based development that is locally driven and 
 cost-shared. The scope for (controlled by one central place), uniform policies and (away from cities) development measures is limited. (away from cities) 
 community development can no longer (if it ever 
 could) be produced as a standardised item of mass 
 
 production. Policy must be Â¯exible to complement and 
 stimulate local abilities (to hold or do something) and business-starting. 
 3.5. The widespread hits/effects of globalisation and 
 rebuilding 
 Changes due to globalisation and money-based rebuilding, either (proof that one thing definitely causes another) or (able to reply or react/quick to respond), are obvious in all 
 parts/areas of the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) and in most walks of life. Most 
 corporations, institutions, state bodies, and non-governmental organisations are being rebuilt in some 
 way. Both the speed of change and its unpredictability and complex difficulty lead to disturbance and doubt. We do not know whether to think about  worldwide 
 rebuilding in all its obviousations as a (not fitting together) 
 or a (atomic) leap in the progress of (a system where people own money and valuable things) (Drucker, 
 1986; Campanella, 1990). Some modern deep thinkers compare it to romanticism, a stage in shared 
 lifewhich (combines different things together so they work as one unit) both traditional values and progress 
 (Hall and Jarvie, 1992). To Giddens (1991) globalisation 
 is a form of advanced modernism, while others, such as 
 Gellner, suggest that it may be after-modern (Gellner, 
 1988; Harvey, 1989). Whatever one's view of the nature 
 and signiÂ®cance of worldwide  rebuilding, it contains a 
 set of external factors which seem likely to go on 
 inÂ¯uencing developments in areas away from cities and opportunities for (away from cities) people for some time to come. 
 3.6. Summary of globalisation hits/effects 
 The most important general hits/effects of globalisation can therefore be summarised brieÂ¯y as: 
  the hit/effect on employment and work; 
  the shrinking of distance through lower costs, and 
 increasing (wasting very little while working or producing something), of move (from one place to another) and communications, evened out by increased awakeness 
 of cultural groups and communities4; 
