 3.7. (away from cities) hits/affects of globalisation 
 Particular hits/effects of globalisation on people in 
 (away from cities) and (off to the side) areas include: 
  worldwide  movements of capital and finance, leading to 
 a shortage of external investment capital; 
  the decline in farming-based employment and in the 
 relative money-based importance of food production, 
 with (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) changes in the farming 
 industry; 
  more and more worldwide  penetration of local markets 
 and increased opportunity for local producers to 
 penetrate worldwide (special place/good job) markets, exposure to 
 increased competition, and the related rebuilding 
 of (a system where people own money and valuable things); 
  growing inter-dependence between areas and activities which are physically distant from each other; 
  increasing efforts to internationalise the terms 
 under which trade happens, and remove money-based and other (blocking things) to trade, including most 
 famously farming-based production payments, for 
 example through the GATT and now the WTO; 
  the (making things all follow the same rules or be copies of the same models) of many (mass market) products, harmonisation of rules and standards 
 (ISO 9000 etc.), lowering of trade (blocking things); 
  the introduction and spread of new technologies, 
 especially ICT and science; 
  worldwide  cultural flows (e.g. through (TV, the Internet, etc.)), 
 obvious in mass person products; 
  (changes in people) including increased personal 
 ability to move around; 
  a new international division of labour in which 
 many unskilled jobs and connected production are 
 moving to the Newly Industrialised Countries. 
 It is not so much the nature of globalisation forces 
 driving change or their general results which 
 distinguishes (away from cities) from city-based  areas, but rather the 
 speciÂ®c forms which these forces take in areas we 
 perceive as `rural'. We focus on them because (away from cities) 
 areas have become (more and more) less self-sufÂ®cient 
 
 193 
 
 and self-contained, and ever more open to the wider 
 forces (money-based, social, political) shaping (related to Europe) 
 and worldwide  development. 
 3.8. Public products (that are bought and sold)  and new demands on the countryside 
 A second major explanatory factor for (away from cities) 
 employment changes is the coming into view of new perceptions of the countryside in rich countries with a high 
 population density (e.g. northern (related to Europe) countries), 
 and the coming into view of new uses and functions which 
 are linked to these new perceptions. 
 The (process of people making, selling, and buying things) contains both private (market) 
 and public (non-market) products (that are bought and sold)  and services. For 
 example, food products and drugs are private products (that are bought and sold)  of the farming-based part/area while pleasant 
 (wide views of nature scenes/wide areas of beautiful land), clean water (also now a private good) and 
 air, (lots of different living things all existing together) and culture are all public products (that are bought and sold). 
 Public products (that are bought and sold)  are those which cannot be directly traded 
 as it is difÂ®cult or impossible to leave out/keep out non-payers 
 from their beneÂ®ts. However, a further feature concerns the important of public perception of `rurality' 
 and the social construction of the countryside in 
 general Ã Newby's `village in the mind'. 
 In many cases public products (that are bought and sold)  are critical useful things/valuable supplies in 
 creating indirect trading activities, for example, they 
 support the development of tourism and recreation, 
 and the perceived (quality of something that makes people like it or want it) of (away from cities) living. They are 
 also important  for human welfare in both (away from cities) and city-based 
 areas. The fact that public products (that are bought and sold)  such as a unspoiled 
 (surrounding conditions) or beautiful (wide view of a nature scene/wide area of beautiful land) cannot be traded 
 directly creates the difÂ®culty of valuing tradable against/compared to/or non-tradable products (that are bought and sold)  which, in the end, places heavy 
 demands on political processes. If a good cannot be 
 traded, should it be protected or preserved only as a 
 natural nice thing? Since non-tradable products (that are bought and sold)  cannot be 
 de-localised, how important are they in (indirectly) 
 beginning and building on local competitive advantages? Who 
 should pay for their maintenance and improvement, 
 and how should it be Â®nanced? 
 Because of the strong link between public products (that are bought and sold) 
 and new city-based  consumption demands on (away from cities) space in 
 richer areas/countries with high population densities, they are a important  inÂ¯uence on both the nature and 
 extent of new (away from cities) money-based activities. For example, 
 city-based  people more and more see areas away from cities as important for rest and recreation, for fresh air and clean 
 water, as offering (ways of living) with advantages over those 
 
 194 
 
 J. Bryden, R. Bollman / Farming-based Money flow 22 (2000) 185Â±197 
 
 in city-based  areas, as having cheaper and more big 
 housing, with positive features of culture and history 
 which are worth preserving, and so on. So, public 
 products (that are bought and sold)  have an more and more important inÂ¯uence on 
 the relative (wanting to beat others in contests) of different areas away from cities 
 and offer scope for local action in a range of diversiÂ®ed money-based, social, cultural and (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) 
 activities. 
 3.9. Human ability to move around 
 Movements of people are a key aspect of (away from cities) 
 change and development. In-traveling, out-traveling, 
 retirement, the keeping/holding onto/remembering or loss of young people, the 
 return of people, commuting, recreation and tourism 
 are all dimensions of this movement. So too are issues 
 of personal and public transport, the location of services (more and more (had everything controlled by one central place)), the location of 
 employment and housing need, provision and cost. 
 Both out-traveling and in-traveling have results for local people, local (communities of people), local (processes of people making, selling, and buying things), local politics and local cultures. In-traveling 
 can offer both threats and opportunities. 
 The movement of people (and in fact businesses/projects) 
 into areas away from cities is not only figured out by/decided by the availability of work and other money-based opportunities, but 
 also by the new values placed on (away from cities) space Ã clean 
 (surrounding conditions), community life, space for fun, pleasant (wide views of nature scenes/wide areas of beautiful land), healthy 'lifestyles', (away from cities) culture, etc., 
 as well as, sometimes, availability of extra 
 buildings and lower cost housing. 
 Previous studies have pointed to/showed two types of traveling from city-based  to areas away from cities: job related traveling 
 and (where there are lots of homes) traveling. Much of the books on 
 city-based  to (away from cities) traveling has assumed that these two 
 types of traveling are closely related and that (related to working on the job) change hints a change in residence. Blanc and 
 Tahar (1997) suggest that there are different factors 
 inÂ¯uencing job related and (where there are lots of homes) traveling and 
 the two types of traveling should be looked at separately. Drawing on a 1985 INSEE survey, they test 
 the relationship between (related to working on the job) and (where there are lots of homes) 
 traveling and point to/show that the two types of traveling 
 are not connected. The analysis suggests a one-way 
 relationship between (related to working on the job) and (where there are lots of homes) 
 ability to move around: (in other words) although (related to working on the job) ability to move around inÂ¯uences (where there are lots of homes) ability to move around, the reverse is unlikely to 
 be true. 
 
 Lower population densities in areas away from cities mean that 
 it is difÂ®cult for people moving to a new location to 
 Â®nd work and people starting a new job to Â®nd 
 housing. However, the (away from cities) housing market is in 
 general easier to access than the (away from cities) labour market. 
 Three reasons are given for this: 
  building one's own house is easier than creating a 
 paid job for oneself; 
  empty houses are common in the countryside 
 after the long period of (away from cities) escape; 
  a person's skills are more specific than housing 
 preferences, and finding a match when there is a 
 shortage is easier on the real estate market than on 
 the job market. 
 This argument is proven as true by Persson et al. 
 (1997) who focus on the decreasing inÂ¯uence of (away from cities) 
 employment availability on people' decisions to 
 move to areas away from cities. They suggest that (way of living) choices 
 are more and more important in maintaining (away from cities) (groups of people/animals/things), both in encouraging people to move to (away from cities) 
 areas and in creating jobs in the area in which they live. 
 A survey of in-traveling workers in (away from cities) Sweden illustrated 
 that employment was not the main reason for their 
 move, and reasons such as moving back to their roots, 
 searching for a sense of community and a non-city-based (way of living) were identiÂ®ed. A survey in southern 
 Canada pointed to/showed a large proportion of families having 
 diversiÂ®ed their sources of income to maintain particular (way of living) choices such as taking holidays, to beneÂ®t children or to sustain family consumption patterns. 
 Persson et al. use the idea  of the `Arena (community of people/all good people in the world)' 
 to illustrate the (many different kinds of people or things) nature of (away from cities) labour markets, 
 the increasing importance of (ways of living) in areas away from cities, 
 and the supply of businesspersons able to work at home, 
 provide business, education and health services. They 
 also develop the idea  of `reach' Ã broadly deÂ®ned 
 as `the ability to agreement the surrounding world 
 in one's world/area/ball of inÂ¯uence' (p. 155). For example, 
 physical reach in the form of links with larger population centres is important in (away from cities) development, but also 
 important are the dimensions of social reach, time 
 reach, knowledge reach and money-based reach in understanding the differences between (away from cities) families, 
 and the effects of new technologies. Basically, this 
 idea  highlights the importance of different kinds of 
 `networks' in going beyond the edges of local 
 space and local markets. 
 
 J. Bryden, R. Bollman / Farming-based Money flow 22 (2000) 185Â±197 
 
 Modern (ways of living) are inÂ¯uenced by worldwide 
 (popular things/general ways things are going) and the pluralistic (features/ qualities/ traits) of `footloose' 
 labour markets. Persson et al. make the point that more 
 bold and confident (ways of living) are developed through a better educated group of workers and the coming into view of knowledge and information based small production units 
 with Â¯exible working conditions. It is more and more 
 possible to make choices about where to live and work 
 based on (things to carefully think about) other than just employment 
 opportunities. They (describe the future) that the search for quality 
 of life will have a signiÂ®cant hit/effect on settlement 
 patterns. 
 Persson et al. go on to suggest that the place given to 
 employment creation in (away from cities) planning is of less 
