 4. End/end result 
 There are many different forces at work leading to a 
 rebuilding of (away from cities) (process of people making, selling, and buying things), (community of people/all good people in the world) and labour 
 markets. What is surprising in a sense is the (state of always working or appearing the same way) of many (away from cities) employment changes Ã the 
 unstoppable decline in farming-based employment, the 
 increase in services employment, especially that 
 linked to tourism and recreation Ã and their clearness with changes in city-based  labour markets (feminisation, move/change to part-time and casual work etc.). However, 
 it is clear that (away from cities) labour markets are still (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) by 
 low-skill, low paid work, that they face huge/extreme 
 possible changes as the growth in knowledge and 
 information work begins to rule the labour market, and that new technology and its (showing the ability to create interesting new things) use in 
 (away from cities) contexts, as well as (related to workers in general) development 
 
 196 
 
 J. Bryden, R. Bollman / Farming-based Money flow 22 (2000) 185Â±197 
 
 and attention to less `tangible' useful things/valuable supplies including 
 `social capital' in its different disguises will be very 
 important in future changes. 
 Existing explanations, either of the new-classical or coreperiphery school, are of little help in terms of understanding differential money-based performance between 
 areas away from cities, even those in (related to where mountains, rivers, cities, etc., are located) (places that are off to the side). 
 They do not account for the differential performance 
 within such (places that are off to the side), nor do they think about/believe important parts of social or (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) capital or the 
 new `consumption' demand on (away from cities) space. We suggest that a new Â®eld of cross-(related to control or punishment) research is 
 opened up, dealing with the multi-(with many flat, polished surfaces) factors 
 which appear important for such explanations. In 
 developing new methods for examining the big thing/the important event of differential performance between areas away from cities, 
 more attention needs to be paid to the leftover/extra term (R) 
 in the production function. An unpacking of `R' 
 necessarily involves paying attention to less `tangible' 
 and because of this less easily measurable factors such as 
 institutional performance and culture, and so hints 
 the need for inter-(related to control or punishment) approaches and methods. 
